### Customer Support API — sample requests
### Use with the VS Code "REST Client" extension (or import into Postman).
### Start the server first:  npm run start:prod

@baseUrl = http://localhost:3000

### 1. Create a ticket (with auto-classification on create)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "customer_id": "DEMO-001",
  "customer_email": "jane.doe@example.com",
  "customer_name": "Jane Doe",
  "subject": "Cannot log in to my account",
  "description": "My password is rejected and now I am locked out, this is critical.",
  "autoClassify": true,
  "tags": ["demo"],
  "metadata": { "source": "web_form", "browser": "Chrome", "device_type": "desktop" }
}

### 2. Create a ticket with explicit category/priority (no classification)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "customer_id": "DEMO-002",
  "customer_email": "bob.smith@example.com",
  "customer_name": "Bob Smith",
  "subject": "Question about my invoice",
  "description": "I was overcharged on my last invoice and would like a refund.",
  "category": "billing_question",
  "priority": "high",
  "metadata": { "source": "email" }
}

### 3. Validation error demo (invalid email → 400)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "customer_id": "DEMO-003",
  "customer_email": "not-an-email",
  "customer_name": "Bad Email",
  "subject": "Broken payload",
  "description": "This payload has an invalid email.",
  "metadata": { "source": "api" }
}

### 4. Bulk import — CSV (50 rows) with auto-classification
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/import?autoClassify=true
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary

--Boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="sample_tickets.csv"
Content-Type: text/csv

< ../tests/fixtures/sample_tickets.csv
--Boundary--

### 5. Bulk import — JSON (20 records)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/import
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary

--Boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="sample_tickets.json"
Content-Type: application/json

< ../tests/fixtures/sample_tickets.json
--Boundary--

### 6. Bulk import — XML (30 tickets)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/import
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary

--Boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="sample_tickets.xml"
Content-Type: application/xml

< ../tests/fixtures/sample_tickets.xml
--Boundary--

### 7. Import with per-row failures (4 of 5 rows invalid)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/import
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary

--Boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="invalid_tickets.csv"
Content-Type: text/csv

< ../tests/fixtures/invalid_tickets.csv
--Boundary--

### 8. Malformed file → 400 with meaningful message
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/import
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=Boundary

--Boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="malformed.json"
Content-Type: application/json

< ../tests/fixtures/malformed.json
--Boundary--

### 9. List all tickets
GET {{baseUrl}}/tickets

### 10. Combined filtering
GET {{baseUrl}}/tickets?category=account_access&priority=urgent

### 11. Filter by status / assignee / tag
GET {{baseUrl}}/tickets?status=new&tag=demo

### 12. Get a single ticket (replace :id)
GET {{baseUrl}}/tickets/REPLACE-WITH-ID

### 13. Auto-classify an existing ticket (replace :id)
POST {{baseUrl}}/tickets/REPLACE-WITH-ID/auto-classify

### 14. Update: assign and resolve (replace :id)
PUT {{baseUrl}}/tickets/REPLACE-WITH-ID
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "assigned_to": "agent.petrenko",
  "status": "resolved"
}

### 15. Delete a ticket (replace :id)
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/tickets/REPLACE-WITH-ID
